ANGELINE BUTLER 🙏🏾🖤💪🏾✨
A tribute to a Black Woman
Portraits by Brandon Perdomo NYC, 2023

"February 13th was our first sit-in, in Nashville. - I think on this day, many of us didn't realize just how important our movement would go to be." - Angeline Butler, excerpt from Sit-In (1960) Dir. Robert M. Young

Black History Month should not just be celebrated during the month of February but all year round. 
To acknowledge Black History month and the upcoming International Women’s day we are dedicating this post to Angeline Butler. It was such a pleasure getting to meet Angeline and be in her presence. 

The biographical information featured in this post came from John Jay College of Criminal Justice:(visit their website to read the full biography)

Biography Source : JOHN JAY COLLEGE OF CRIMINAL JUSTICE, 
https://www.jjay.cuny.edu/faculty/angeline-butler

GIVE IN PART 1
Love the Botticelli composition and statuesque posing.
Beautiful contemporary renaissance vibes.
Words from the artist below:
_________________________________________________⁠

"The concept for ‘Give In Part l’ symbolizes the deconstruction of toxic masculinity while having a safe space amongst a selected group of people. 

I wanted a shot that demonstrated a man actively Giving In to energies that makeup his true essence- a liberated balance of masculine and feminine energy. I’ve noticed that a lot of men are willing to journey through this construct while being surrounded by those who love them and want the individual to flourish internally & externally. 

During my entire life, career, and journey I battled with the presence of toxic masculinity and witnessed how this facade stripped my existence. As a child, I intuitively noticed I inhabited both the masculine and feminine energy. While discovering my natural essence, I chose to venture into fulfilling the “masculine image” because that’s what boys do, right? It didnt work for me.

 I always felt like an imposter playing the hyper masculine roles, kissing girls in shows, wearing the stereotypical masculine silhouette and clothes, strategically structuring the natural melody of my voice to fit the expected masculine vocal pattern, playing nearly every sport and rough housing with the guys, creating stories and scenarios to hide my sexuality from loved ones, my relationship with the divine- and the list continues. The listed dilemma’s all fall upon (most) boys at a very young age and challenges how they navigate their lives. At the age of 23 I realized running from my essence was no longer necessary, and that was the start of learning to love myself."

In this Dialogues show, we feature the NY premieres of our call for multimedia proposals by Robert McClure and Mare Hirsch, Brian Harnetty, and HyeKyung Lee and Christian Faur. McClure/Hirsch's contours snared, in warp and weft explores melodic shapes and contours while the electronics provide an interactive backdrop weaving together the instrumental elements. Harnetty's The Workbench draws together sonic fragments of voice, memory, and long instrumental lines to create a sonic portrait of Harnetty’s father. This Saturday at 3pm & 7pm, join @cp4p_international for performances of “I Will Dance With Those Oak Tree As Long As” at Alchemical Studios. 

A stunning mix of puppetry, mime, storytelling, dance, song, and voice tells the story of Gilgamesh, the oldest surviving epic poem.

In March of 1988, in Halabja, Iraq, Saddam Hussein’s regime attacked Kurdish peoples through the use of chemical weapons as part of the Anfal ethnic cleansing campaign. Set in a carpet store at this time, I will dance with those oak trees as long as takes us on a poetic voyage into the life of three Kurdish women, inspired by the poetry of Kajal Ahmad and the characters Gilgamesh, Enkidu, and Ninsun from the world’s most ancient epic poem: Gilgamesh. Carpets, chairs, and strings create the environment in which two actresses interpret the three different women and how they react to a violent and unstable outside world. 

Accompanied by soundscapes inspired by traditional Kurdish music, this international duo uses objects, puppets, and a multilayered world of reality, dreams, memories, and visions to explore the question of what it means to be a hero when you have no other choice.

Performed by Audrey Rose Dégez @audreyrosey33 and Daria Holovchanska @d_golovchanskaya

Producer, Playwright, & Director: Audrey Rose Dégez
Puppet Master, Lighting & Sound Designer, Movement & Object Director: Daria Holovchanska
Stage Manager: Berivan Alothman
Produced by: CP4P International Productions
